                "abstract": [
                    {
                        "value": "The Edith Segal Collection on Labor Activism (dated 1918-1980) contains a small assortment of items created and collected by Edith Segal. Segal (1906-1997) was an American dancer, teacher, and poet from New York City. The collection contains various items related to labor activism and life in early-20th century America, and consist of a scrapbook from World War I, a pamphlet on New York Child Labor and Compulsory Education Laws (1918); a flyer for a 1936 May Day rally; a flyer for a play satirizing the Civilian Conservation Corps; an article from \u003cspan class=\"ead-emph ead-emph-italic\"\u003eHome and Education\u003c/span\u003e (1941), a magazine for Jewish mothers and teachers; and a report from the United Workers Cooperative Colony 50th Anniversary (1977). The collection also contains German-language ephemera from the Prolet Buehne in New York City, and two drafts written by Segal, photographs of Labor Day rallies in Detroit (circa 1937-1938), and reproductions of photographs taken by Lewis W. Hine for the National Child Labor Committee.",
                        "id": "aspace_6f0451e0d535add39484359327d9ddd4"
                    }
                ],
